# Payments Domain – Domain Model

# Purpose

This document defines the core domain model of the Payments Domain, including entities, attributes, relationships, and business rules.

It represents the conceptual structure of the domain and serves as the foundation for implementation, event design, and API contracts.

---

# Core Entities

## Payment

The central aggregate representing a financial transaction lifecycle.

### Attributes

| Attribute      | Type              | Description                              |
| -------------- | ----------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| paymentId      | UUID              | Unique identifier for the payment        |
| status         | PaymentStatus     | Current state of the payment lifecycle   |
| amount         | Decimal           | Monetary value of the payment            |
| currency       | String            | ISO currency code (e.g., EUR, USD)       |
| createdAt      | DateTime          | Timestamp when payment was created       |
| updatedAt      | DateTime          | Last modification timestamp              |
| clientId       | UUID              | Identifier of the initiating client      |
| payerId        | UUID              | Identifier of the payer                  |
| payeeId        | UUID              | Identifier of the payee                  |
| providerId     | String            | External payment provider reference      |
| idempotencyKey | String            | Key used to prevent duplicate processing |
| failureReason  | String (nullable) | Reason for failure if payment failed     |

### Business Rules

* A Payment must always have a unique `paymentId`.
* A Payment must have exactly one currency.
* A Payment must transition through valid states only.
* A Payment cannot be modified once it reaches a terminal state (Completed, Failed, Cancelled).
* A Payment must be idempotent with respect to `idempotencyKey`.
* Amount must be greater than zero.
* Status transitions must follow the defined lifecycle rules.

---

## PaymentIntent

Represents an intention to perform a payment before execution.

### Attributes

| Attribute | Type         | Description             |
| --------- | ------------ | ----------------------- |
| intentId  | UUID         | Unique identifier       |
| amount    | Decimal      | Intended payment amount |
| currency  | String       | ISO currency code       |
| clientId  | UUID         | Initiating client       |
| status    | IntentStatus | Current intent state    |
| createdAt | DateTime     | Creation timestamp      |

### Business Rules

* A PaymentIntent may or may not result in a Payment.
* A PaymentIntent can expire if not acted upon.
* A PaymentIntent must be validated before conversion to Payment.

---

## PaymentTransaction

Represents an execution instance with an external provider.

### Attributes

| Attribute         | Type                | Description                      |
| ----------------- | ------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| transactionId     | UUID                | Unique transaction identifier    |
| paymentId         | UUID                | Associated Payment               |
| providerReference | String              | External provider transaction ID |
| status            | TransactionStatus   | Current execution status         |
| initiatedAt       | DateTime            | Execution start time             |
| completedAt       | DateTime (nullable) | Completion time                  |

### Business Rules

* A Payment may have multiple PaymentTransactions (retries or provider changes).
* Only one successful transaction is required for Payment completion.
* Transaction status must reflect provider response accurately.

---

## PaymentProvider

Represents an external system that processes payments.

### Attributes

| Attribute           | Type           | Description              |
| ------------------- | -------------- | ------------------------ |
| providerId          | String         | Unique identifier        |
| name                | String         | Provider name            |
| status              | ProviderStatus | Availability status      |
| supportedCurrencies | List<String>   | Supported currency codes |

### Business Rules

* A provider may be unavailable temporarily.
* Payments must fail gracefully if no provider is available.
* Provider selection must be abstracted from business logic.

---

## Refund

Represents reversal of a completed payment.

### Attributes

| Attribute | Type         | Description                |
| --------- | ------------ | -------------------------- |
| refundId  | UUID         | Unique identifier          |
| paymentId | UUID         | Original payment reference |
| amount    | Decimal      | Refund amount              |
| status    | RefundStatus | Current state              |
| reason    | String       | Reason for refund          |
| createdAt | DateTime     | Timestamp                  |

### Business Rules

* Refunds can only be created for completed payments.
* Refund amount cannot exceed original payment amount.
* Partial refunds are allowed.
* Refunds must be traceable to original payment.

---

# Entity Relationships

## Payment → PaymentTransaction

* One Payment can have many PaymentTransactions.
* Each PaymentTransaction belongs to exactly one Payment.
* Payment success depends on at least one successful transaction.

---

## Payment → Refund

* One Payment can have zero or many Refunds.
* Refunds are always linked to a single Payment.
* Refunds cannot exist without a completed Payment.

---

## PaymentIntent → Payment

* One PaymentIntent may generate zero or one Payment.
* Relationship is optional and depends on execution outcome.

---

## Payment → PaymentProvider

* A Payment is processed by exactly one PaymentProvider per transaction.
* Provider selection is abstracted and not stored as business logic.

---

## PaymentTransaction → PaymentProvider

* Each transaction is executed against one provider.
* Providers may differ across retries or fallback scenarios.

---

# Domain Constraints

## Consistency Rules

* Payment state transitions must be atomic and validated.
* No Payment may skip intermediate lifecycle states.

## Idempotency Rules

* Duplicate PaymentRequests with same idempotencyKey must return same Payment.

## Temporal Rules

* A Payment cannot be marked Completed before successful transaction confirmation.
* Refunds must occur after Payment completion.

## Financial Rules

* Payment amount must always be positive.
* Refund total must not exceed original payment amount.

## Integrity Rules

* All Payments must be traceable through at least one PaymentTransaction.
* No orphan Refunds are allowed.

---

# Aggregates

## Payment Aggregate (Root)

* Payment
* PaymentTransaction
* Refund

Rules:

* Payment is the aggregate root.
* All modifications to child entities must go through Payment.
* Consistency is enforced at Payment level.

---

# Notes

* This model is technology-agnostic.
* It does not define database schema or API structure.
* It is intended to guide implementation and maintain domain consistency.
* Any deviation must be documented via ADR.
